    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3374350192" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3374350192" />
    <a title="jade" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11030012-jade"><img alt="jade" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562419355p2/11030012.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3374350192?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="jade" class="user" itemprop="url" name="jade" href="/user/show/11030012-jade">jade</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780006140450" href="/book/show/655778.Appointment_With_Death">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">murder mystery aficionados who love a good villain &amp; don't mind a wonky ending</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to jade by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/107881343-library-girl-reading">library girl reading</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11030012-jade?shelf=buddy-reads">buddy-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11030012-jade?shelf=murder-mysteries">murder-mysteries</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3374350192" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14628669192826117443"><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>“on the whole, you know, people tell you the truth. because it is easier! because it is less strain on the inventive faculties! you can tell one lie -- or two lies -- or three lies or even four lies -- but you cannot lie all the time. and so -- the truth becomes plain.”</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br/>when poirot goes on a holiday, we all know that dead bodies will inevitably follow him -- as they also do in this novel when he makes a trip to egypt, israel, and jordan.<br/><br/>initially, poirot takes a bit of a backseat as w</span>
  <span id="freeText14628669192826117443" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>“on the whole, you know, people tell you the truth. because it is easier! because it is less strain on the inventive faculties! you can tell one lie -- or two lies -- or three lies or even four lies -- but you cannot lie all the time. and so -- the truth becomes plain.”</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br />when poirot goes on a holiday, we all know that dead bodies will inevitably follow him -- as they also do in this novel when he makes a trip to egypt, israel, and jordan.<br /><br />initially, poirot takes a bit of a backseat as we follow <b>the boynton family</b> on their trip to visit petra. at the heart of this family sits a nightmare of a wicked stepmother that puts other poirot villains to shame: an emotionally abusive, gaslighting, sadist of a matriarch who used to be a prison warden.<br /><br />yeah. you can imagine what life’s like for her kids.<br /><br />we see their fucked-up family dynamics and mrs. boynton’s incessantly abusive behavior mostly through the eyes of three outsiders: <b>jefferson cope</b>, a friend of the family with a soft spot for nadine, who married the eldest boynton kid. there’s also <b>dr. gerard</b>, an older french doctor, and <b>dr. king</b>, a young woman who just got her md.<br /><br />the latter two, especially, have highly interesting conversations on the psychology of the boynton family -- though subject to the weird beliefs of its time, it still serves as a solid way to keep the reader engaged until poirot starts sticking his nose into the murder business.<br /><br /><b>the setting</b> should’ve been tremendously interesting, but was rarely even described beyond there being caves, oppressive heat, and stupid arab servants (sigh). which was a pity, honestly, because i know christie can work magic with her atmospheric writing. but the beauty of cairo and petra -- heck, even of the hotel -- were rarely felt.<br /><br /><b>the individual boynton family members</b> and their aspirations were the highlight of this book for me. you feel keenly for all of them and their predicament, breathing a collective sigh of relief right alongside them once the old bird croaks her last. from marital problems, first loves, protective sibling instincts, and outright delusions -- they’ve got it all.<br /><br />it was fun to see poirot <b>set a challenge</b> for himself of solving the mystery within 24 hours; it creates a greater sense of urgency and pace. he eventually solves it based purely on psychological deduction and why and how the people involved lied. so no hard evidence -- and that made it particularly difficult to guess the true culprit.<br /><br />because of that, the ending came across as a bit <b>disjointed and disappointing</b> to me, and some aspects of it were unintentionally hilarious.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[such as ALL the boynton family members ending up lying and concealing key pieces of testimony in order to (unnecessarily) protect each other. idk, i found it wildly hilarious that they all passed by mrs. boynton’s corpse sometime during the day, thought the family member that walked up to her before they did was the one that killed her, and instantly decided to cover it up.<br /><br />it was almost as funny as the strangely disney-esque happy ending. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />in conclusion, not the very <i>best</i> poirot in terms of the actual mystery, but it does have a couple of very entertaining characters and interesting dynamics. and i do always like a good villain!<br /><br />✎ <i>3.5 stars.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="14628669192826117443" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

