<div id="review_3973357990" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3973357990" />
    <a title="Karina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62428250-karina"><img alt="Karina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632727821p2/62428250.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3973357990?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karina" href="/user/show/62428250-karina">Karina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781579126926" href="/book/show/140361.Appointment_with_Death">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3973357990" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9524490428079756691">3.5<br/><br/>&quot;&apos;So much so that he was content to leave his children completely at her mercy from the financial point of view. In my country, Mr. Cope, is is impossible by law to do such a thing.&apos;&quot;<br/>Mr. Cope rose.<br/>&apos;In America,&apos; he said, &apos;we&apos;re great believers in absolute freedom.&apos;<br/>Dr. Gerard rose also. He was unimpressed by the remark. He had heard it made before by people of many different nationalities. The illusion that freedom is the prerogative of one&apos;s own particular race is fairly widespread.<br/>Dr. Gerard </span>
  <span id="freeText9524490428079756691" style="display:none">3.5<br /><br />"'So much so that he was content to leave his children completely at her mercy from the financial point of view. In my country, Mr. Cope, is is impossible by law to do such a thing.'"<br />Mr. Cope rose.<br />'In America,' he said, 'we're great believers in absolute freedom.'<br />Dr. Gerard rose also. He was unimpressed by the remark. He had heard it made before by people of many different nationalities. The illusion that freedom is the prerogative of one's own particular race is fairly widespread.<br />Dr. Gerard was wiser. He knew that no race, no country and no individual could be described as free. But he also knew that there were different degrees of bondage." (PAGE 42)<br /><br />While it was quotable and a fun read, I just found it okay. It took a while to get to the premise and have Hercule Poirot make his entrance but it was still enjoyable. The killer wasn't even in my vicinity! Christie and Poirot came together to surprise us on that one. <br /><br />I will say I am a lover of character dialogue and Christie has a genius of letting us know who the players are what is in their hearts. She shows us good vs evil while she entertains us into her simple yet complicated mind. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9524490428079756691" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


