<span id="freeTextContainer7864865931549452673">This was a re-read for me, but first time in English. I had also the audiobook playing along. The audiobook was narrated by the actor Hugh Fraser (he plays as Hastings in the tv series), who did an excellent job. <br/>I read this book during my teens and I couldn’t remember anything about the storyline. I think because I did not find it that memorable.<br/>This is not one of her best works, but it is still entertaining.<br/>Yesterday I watched the adaptation for the TV for the first time, the one with David Su</span>
  <span id="freeText7864865931549452673" style="display:none">This was a re-read for me, but first time in English. I had also the audiobook playing along. The audiobook was narrated by the actor Hugh Fraser (he plays as Hastings in the tv series), who did an excellent job. <br />I read this book during my teens and I couldn’t remember anything about the storyline. I think because I did not find it that memorable.<br />This is not one of her best works, but it is still entertaining.<br />Yesterday I watched the adaptation for the TV for the first time, the one with David Suchet, my favourite Poirot, but that adaptation is very different and very dramatic with scenes of child abuse.<br />There is a 1981 movie adaptation with Peter Ustinov, which I have also not watched but I heard that it is close to the book.<br />As for this book, I’m not sure what is missing in the plot, but it did not quite impress me. Perhaps clarity? Or perhaps Poirot’s presence? He makes a late entrance after all. And I found Poirot’s deductions and explanation a bit confusing and the ending a bit disappointing.<br />Regardless, Dame Christie remains one of my favourite authors and the best cure for a (my) reading slump.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7864865931549452673" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

